* The purpose of the settlement benchmark is to provide a means of
comparing the settlement efficiency of different markets and to track
the evolution of settlement performance in individual markets over
time. The benchmark incorporates the four components which, combined
together, reflect the overall cost to market patricipants of failed
trades. These include average trade size, local market interest rates,
the proportion of trades that fail, and the length of time for which
they fail. By converting information back into a base currency,
comparisons between markets become possible. The benchmarks are
expressed as a score out of a maximum 100. The lower the score the
higher the effective operational costs of failed transactions in any
given market.
