<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / International Company News: Ameritech in Dollars 2.25bn
write-down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ameritech, the Chicago-based regional telephone company, is to take a
non-financial charge of Dollars 2.25bn net in the fourth quarter, resulting
in a loss for the year. The charge represents a write-down in the company's
asset value to reflect a more competitive market.
Ameritech's move follows that of fellow regional phone companies US West,
which took a Dollars 3.2bn charge in the third quarter of last year, and
Bell Atlantic, which took a charge of Dollars 2.15bn in the third quarter of
this year.
Ameritech said it was reducing its net asset value from Dollars 17.1bn to
Dollars 13.4bn. The Dollars 3.7bn write-down is reduced to Dollars 2.25bn
after tax. Shareholders' equity will fall from Dollars 8.05bn to Dollars
5.74bn. Last year Ameritech made net profits of Dollars 1.5bn.
The company said that in all the states in which it operates it is now
regulated on the basis of price caps, rather than by the older system of
return on assets. It is therefore free to reduce its assets to what it sees
as their commercial value, rather than the higher figure on which its
allowable return was calculated before.
At the same time, Ameritech said it would shorten its depreciation
schedules, which were also set previously by the regulators.
It said it would now fully depreciate its analog switches and depreciate its
more modern digital switches over seven years instead of 17.
</TEXT>
