<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Salvesen to sell pollution control and brick units:
Distribution and hire group looks at disposals as profits flatten
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Christian Salvesen, the distribution and specialist hire company, is looking
to sell its pollution control and brick manufacturing divisions by the end
of this financial year, raising around Pounds 60m to invest in its core
businesses. The disposals would almost halve its Pounds 129m of net
borrowings and Salvesen is looking at acquisitions in European distribution,
after the success of its Pounds 84m purchase of Swift, the industrial
distribution company.
The group's results, however, were less upbeat. Pre-tax profits for the six
months to September rose by 1 per cent to Pounds 41.4m, despite the impact
of Swift, which was purchased in October 1993.
Salvesen issued a profits warning last February, after a rapid downturn from
Aggreko, its specialist plant hire business. Aggreko's latest figures reveal
a turnround in the US, which achieved 23 per cent growth. Generator hire for
the World Cup helped, but it also benefited from large cost cuts. However,
Aggreko's European businesses offset most of this improvement.
Light &amp; Sound Design, acquired for Pounds 7.6m in 1991, slumped into loss,
and Salvesen plans to trim its operations. This could lead to second-half
write-downs, which will offset likely profits from the sale of the brick
business. Overall, the specialist hire division saw operating profits fall
4.5 per cent to Pounds 14.8m.
Distribution now accounts for almost half of Salvesen's Pounds 319.3m
(Pounds 262.3m) turnover, and the division's profits rose 20 per cent to
Pounds 21.6m, boosted by a Pounds 5.7m contribution from Swift.
Mr Chris Masters, chief executive, said Swift had been fully integrated into
the division, and performed better than expectations. It has given Salvesen
a substantial push into distribution for industrial companies, which he sees
as a growth area in the UK and Europe. The group won new contracts during
the period, from Texaco Oils, BASF and Lucas Industries.
The UK food sector remains competitive, but Salvesen has renewed
distribution contracts with Safeway and Haagen-Dazs, on 'reasonable' terms.
However, profits at the US division fell 15 per cent to Dollars 6.1m (Pounds
3.7m).
Food Services profits fell 13 per cent to Pounds 6.5m, while the brick
manufacturing division more than doubled to Pounds 3.6m.
Interests payments rose from Pounds 1.7m to Pounds 4.7m, reflecting the
impact of the Swift acquisition, added to a further Pounds 41.1m (Pounds
40.4m) of capital expenditure for the interim period.
The company is paying a 3.4p dividend, up from 3.3p. Earnings per share were
10.5p (10.29p).
Details, Page 24
</TEXT>
