<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Finance Ministry orders derivative transparency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's financial institutions will be required for the first time to
disclose information about their derivative holdings, the Finance Ministry
said yesterday.
The disclosure rule is expected to focus on the type of derivatives
contracts and their value, and could be enforced as early as next March,
according to ministry officials.
The market in derivatives, securities such as futures and options contracts,
developed in Japan in the late 1980s. Trading in many widely-used
instruments is highly circumscribed by the Finance Ministry, but Japanese
banks and brokers have been active in developing a market in those
derivatives that are permitted.
In the last year regulators watched with alarm as the highly-geared nature
of derivatives increased the exposure of companies to heavy losses. Earlier
this month, one Japanese broker, Tokyo Securities reported that it had lost
Y32bn (Pounds 207m) from contracts on currency options, a sum equivalent to
more than a third of the value of its shareholders' equity.
The authorities have expressed deepening concern about the market, as
Japanese companies previously were required to give only sketchy details
about their derivatives portfolios.
</TEXT>
