<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Just as nobody is so prudish as a reformed tart, so no one is more devoted
to integrity than an ex-MP. In Without Walls: Bad Ideas of the Twentieth
Century (9pm, Channel 4) Matthew Parris excoriates the public relations
industry with a sense of outrage that occasionally topples into moral
confusion. Does the fact that the eye-witness of alleged atrocities in
Kuwait is a royal and the daughter of the ambassador to the US automatically
discredit her testimony? And why discount U2's charity work simply because
Parris accusingly brands them 'the world's richest band'?
Much of the film shows Parris being groomed (haircut, new underpants,
pedicure) by a PR lady called Shaa Wasmund (if it's an anagram I haven't
worked it out yet). 'I have felt conscious of the presence of a camera all
morning,' he observes with the percipience that marked him out for politics
and journalism. And there's the rub: he hates PR because it can corrupt his
own profession. He may have a point, but this exercise in over-decent
exposure doth protest too much.
</TEXT>
