<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Accountancy rules relief attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans to release 90 per cent of companies from compliance with most
accounting standards were attacked yesterday by the Chartered Association of
Certified Accountants.
The accountancy profession's working party on standards, commissioned by the
Accounting Standards Board, has said that small companies should be exempt
from most of the rules.
The working party said complicated accounting standards were an inefficient
burden and could lead to the loss of a competitive advantage when private
information was disclosed.
It proposed that small companies, as defined by the Companies Act, should be
exempt from most standards and all new ones unless a special case was made
by the standards board.
But Mr Peter Langard, vice-president of the chartered association, said the
proposals - which are out for public consultation - could reduce the
comparability of accounts for companies 'which form the backbone of British
industry'.
The chartered association said the cost of compliance with standards would
not be removed by the proposals because as the main burden for companies was
meeting the requirements of the Companies Act.
Mr Langard said: 'Accounting standards help both preparers and users to make
sense of existing rules, which often fail to prescribe an appropriate
accounting base.
'Exemption could be made on a case-by-case basis only, when it can be
demonstrated that there are significant cost burdens arising from the
application of a particular standard.'
</TEXT>
