<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / New mortgages fall in October
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fresh evidence of the sluggishness of the mortgage market came yesterday as
it emerged that new home loans by banks fell more than 10 per cent in
October compared with September.
The number of new loans approved but not yet undertaken was also down
slightly at 29,081, from 29,718 in September. While this was higher than in
October last year, the average value of loans approved - Pounds 50,400 - was
scarcely more than the equivalent in 1993. This contrasts with the summer,
when average values of loans approved were 10 per cent higher than in the
previous year.
The figures, released by the British Bankers' Association, show new lending
last month, both in gross and net terms, below the levels of October 1993.
Mr Tim Sweeney, BBA director-general, said the figures mirrored the fall in
new home loans from building societies last month.
He suggested that the poorer figures for October might have reflected
September's 'good month' in the mortgage market. However, new net lending by
banks in September this year was less than in September last year.
