<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / House sale lull hits land prices: Inland Revenue report says
improvement in property market has petered out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rapid increases in housing land prices seen earlier this year have slowed
considerably as the expected housing market upturn has failed to
materialise, says a report by Inland Revenue valuation officers.
The findings of the Revenue's district valuation officers provide one of the
most comprehensive guides to the health of the residential, commercial and
agricultural property markets.
Their latest report shows that 956,000 property transactions, mostly house
sales, were notified to the Revenue in England and Wales in the first nine
months of this year - 10 per cent more than in the corresponding period last
year.
The valuation office said that in spite of this improvement 'the purchaser
is still very much in command of the market, making for predominantly static
prices in all parts of the country'.
The pace of improvement, moreover, had slowed as a sharp increase in sales
activity in the spring was followed by an earlier than usual summer lull.
This trend had continued in the autumn with reported transactions 6 per cent
lower in September than in the corresponding month last year.
The report says the number of housing transactions is at a level last seen
in 1980, with purchases being dictated by necessity rather than desire.
House prices had seen very little increase, with average housing values in
England and Wales rising by just 1.3 per cent in the 12 months to the end of
October.
The valuation office said: 'The regional markets show very little variation,
with the majority exhibiting only marginally higher values over (the
previous) six months.'
Only Wales, south-east England and outer London had shown 'overall increases
of any substance'.
The slowdown in the housing market in the summer and autumn has led to a
corresponding reduction in the pace of housing land price increases, which
rose sharply earlier this year.
The report says: 'The increased activity seen in the previous reporting
period appears to have subsided now that the anticipated upturn in the
housing market has not materialised.'
Builders were continuing to restock with land but were no longer 'prepared
to bid up prices except in favoured locations such as the Home Counties,
where marked increases in value have been seen for sites within striking
distance of the M25'.
There were also big differences in land price movements between northern and
southern regions of England. Increases in north-west and northern England
had been limited.
The market in the southern half of the country, by comparison, had generally
been buoyant apart from 'pockets of inactivity where employment in
long-established industries has declined such as at English China Clays in
St Austell (Cornwall)'.
The Revenue said yesterday: 'Overall district valuers are of the opinion
that an upturn in the housing market is a prerequisite of any further
improvement in the resi-dential building land market.'
Property Market Report, Autumn 1994. Valuation Office Agency, Room G33, New
Court, Carey Street, London WC2A 2JE. Pounds 30.
