<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Think-tank calls for farming 'safety net'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Agricultural subsidies to farmers in the European Union should be phased out
and replaced by a 'safety net' of social and environmental payments in rural
areas, the Royal Institute of International Affairs will recommend this
week.
The radical proposals from the Chatham House think-tank are the latest in a
groundswell of pressure for further reform of the Common Agricultural
Policy, intensified by the proposed entry of east European countries into
the EU.
In a 10-point programme of reform to be unveiled in Brussels on Thursday,
the institute calls for a comprehensive policy for rural development to
replace the CAP and take on a comparable political importance. It says this
would involve 'organisational changes' in the European Commission and the
Council of Ministers - a hint that farm policy would be better dictated in
future by a wider range of ministers than just agriculture ministers.
The institute says the difficult negotiations leading to the MacSharry
reforms of 1992 left European agriculture ministers reluctant to embark on
further big changes. But it says the reform process is incomplete and
further change is needed 'sooner rather than later' to address the
integration of eastern Europe, with its vast agricultural potential.
The report, based on eight months of deliberations by European policymakers
and agricultural experts, is designed to coincide with the arrival of the
new Commission next year. It recommends that support prices for all CAP
products be cut to near world market levels over a period of five to seven
years and border tariffs should be correspondingly lowered.
Existing compensation paid to farmers for price cuts should be phased out,
while compensation for reductions in support prices in as yet unreformed
sectors, such as sugar, should not be related in any way to output levels in
order to discourage overproduction. It should also carry specific time
limits.
The institute wants production quotas for sugar and milk to be transferable
across borders in the short term, and to be eliminated in the long term. By
contrast, payments for adopting environmentally-friendly practices should be
available to all farmers.
It calls for member states to have greater freedom to introduce social and
environmental schemes provided these are strictly controlled by the EU to
prevent unfair competition. The extent of EU financing for such programmes
should vary according to member states' ability to pay - a policy designed
to promote social cohesion within the EU.
The report says: 'Adopting such a programme would leave the EU with an
agricultural support system which protects the farmer from market collapse
but serves only as a safety net.
'It would facilitate the entry into the union of the countries of central
and eastern Europe without unacceptable budgetary cost . . . Above all it
would allow the EU to develop rural policies which were more closely attuned
to the social and environmental objectives of the union.'
Sir Michael Franklin, chairman of the European research programme and
co-author of the report, said: 'We're clear the best route is through a
carefully-constructed programme over several years to minimise disruption
and give investors and farmers a greater degree of confidence and certainty
on which to base their plans.'
Farm leaders attack, Page 33
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9641 Regulation of Agricultural Marketing.
    P01   Agricultural Production-Crops.
    P02   Agricultural Production-Livestock.
    P07   Agricultural Services.
</IN>
<XX>
