<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Sleaze goes to university after government reforms: Claims
of financial impropriety in higher education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sleaze allegations have hit the government's reforms of further and higher
education this month.
Yesterday Portsmouth University, a former polytechnic which owes its
independent status to government reforms, launched an investigation into
claims that its vice-chancellor muddled his expense claims for foreign
trips.
The university said yesterday that it had given Professor Neil Merritt a
'formal warning' over the allegations, and said that a vote of no-confidence
in him supported by 93 per cent of staff was 'hardly surprising, given the
one-sided nature of the information' drip fed to them. The members and remit
of the independent inquiry will be decided next week.
This is only the latest of several allegations of dubious financial
behaviour by university and college governors.
One quango, the Further Education Funding Council for England, has
recommended dismissal for the governing boards of two further education
colleges, in Birmingham and Derby. Both were freed from local authority
control and incorporated as independent institutions in April 1993.
At St Philip's Roman Catholic Sixth Form College, Birmingham, the governors
said they were determined to close the college in spite of opposition from
parents and staff. At Derby College, Wilmorton, governors were asked to
repay illegal payments of about Pounds 16,000.
The most serious incident came at the end of October, when the funding
council which covers higher education ordered Huddersfield University -
which gained its current status in 1992 - not to pay a planned Pounds
400,000 golden handshake to its departing vice-chancellor, saying it was
'possibly illegal'.
Higher education in particular is divided over how to respond to the
problems. Universities are traditionally autonomous and are alarmed by any
indications that they cannot use their autonomy responsibly.
But lecturers' unions say that accountability in the sector has been
weakened by the government's decision to incorporate colleges and
universities as bodies run on the same lines as limited companies.
Huddersfield has taken the most drastic action so far. It used powers given
to it by the 1988 and 1992 education acts to remove the local authority,
staff and student representatives from its governing body.
Then it gave its vice-chancellor, Professor Kenneth Durrands, a pay rise of
45 per cent, backdated by four months, to be followed by a severance package
of about Pounds 400,000 - out of a total annual turnover of about Pounds
55m. The total involved was only revealed after a National Audit Office
investigation, which MPs from the Public Accounts Committee ordered to be
made public.
This had been agreed in spite of an overwhelming vote of no-confidence in
the governing council by academic staff.
The university agreed to set aside the package after the funding council's
intervention. The funding council is anxious not to make incursions on
university autonomy, however, and said that renegotiating a fresh package
for Prof Durrands was 'a matter for the university'.
It is now working on a guidance note for governors, although it stresses
this will not include binding regulations.
The Committee of Vice-chancellors and Principals, which represents the
managers of all universities in the UK, wants to avoid any resort to
legislation to solve the problems.
It opposed Huddersfield's action in dismissing its local authority and staff
representatives. 'Huddersfield was the only new university which used the
powers it was given by the government,' it said.
</TEXT>
