<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Builders warn on cuts in Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government efforts to raise private finance for railways, roads, schools,
hospitals and other infrastructure should not be used as an excuse to cut
public spending, building industry leaders said yesterday.
The eve-of-Budget warning follows a recent statement by the chancellor that
spending departments would be required to consider whether there was a
private finance alternative before approving public spending projects.
Mr Hugh Try, chairman of the Building Employers ConFederation, the biggest
industry trade association, stressed yesterday that the initiative 'was
intended to supplement, and not replace, existing planned public
expenditure'.
Construction companies are worried that Mr Clarke may announce further cuts
in the road programme to curtail public spending.
They also expect the chancellor to make a feature of the private finance
initiative - possibly announcing approval for some light rail schemes and
more privately financed roads.
Industry leaders say, however, that they will be dismayed if this is
accom-panied by substantial cuts in public investment on construction.
Mr Try said yesterday: 'We shall be monitoring the position carefully to see
that future public sector capital expenditure is maintained at the necessary
levels with additional schemes being brought on stream through the private
finance initiative.'
Mr Clarke told a a Confederation of British Industry conference this month
that he expected private finance to provide 'the main source of growth' for
public investment projects.
He said the requirement on public sector bodies to investigate private
finance alternatives would concentrate 'finite public capital provision on
those areas where, for whatever reason, private finance is not possible'.
The Building Employers Confederation said it was concerned that progress on
the private finance initiative was 'unnecessarily slow.'
More effective procedures needed to be developed by the Treasury and other
government departments for dealing with projects, it said. Banks and
construction companies also needed to be more positive in bringing schemes
forward.
Mr Try said ministers had promised to overcome unnecessary bureaucracy and
constraints. It was also up to 'the construction industry to rise to the
challenge to deal with the risks and deliver value for money and profit from
its investment'.
</TEXT>
