<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Safety cover curbs spark fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Safety inspectors have been asked to consult Whitehall before taking action
next year against companies with inadequate insurance for deaths and
injuries at work as concern grows about proposed new policy conditions.
Changes planned to employers' liability policies renewed from January 'are
likely to lead to compliance problems' for some employers, the Department of
Employment acknowledged yesterday.
The department has asked to be informed before Health and Safety Executive
inspectors begin action against companies under the the 1969 Employers
Liability Act, which requires employers to have insurance policies worth at
least Pounds 2m per claim.
Companies have had little difficulty meeting the terms of the act because
insurance companies have provided unlimited-cover policies. However
insurance companies faced with rapidly rising claims have decided that in
future employers' liability policies will have a basic claims limit of
Pounds 10m.
This threatens to create problems for corporate groups because new
Department of Employment guidelines suggest that each subsidiary company
will have to have Pounds 2m cover 'in all circumstances'. This may leave
each subsidiary without adequate cover if a large claim were made elsewhere
in the group.
Representatives of the Association of British Insurers are expected to meet
employment department officials on Thursday in an attempt to resolve the
impasse.
The department said yesterday it had been 'consulting informally' with the
Health and Safety Executive as well as the association to gauge the extent
of the problem 'with a view to finding an acceptable solution'.
The executive, which is responsible for policing the act, said about 10
companies a year were prosecuted for failing to display a certificate
showing that they were properly insured.
Meanwhile, the association expressed confidence that new insurance products
would become available to allow companies to buy extra cover, both to meet
the legal requirements and to allow proper cover against large-scale
disasters. It expects the market for 'top-up' liability insurance to be a
specialised sector.
Questions also remain over whether insurance and reinsurance companies will
make sufficient capacity available to meet large companies' demands and over
whether restrictions on the new products will be compatible with the
employment department's guidelines.
</TEXT>
