<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Aftershock of rebels' revolt will rumble on
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the end, only a handful of Tories defied the government last night but
the consequences of the mini-rebellion are likely to rumble on for months,
with serious consequences for the government, as well as the rebels.
Most of the 18 Eurosceptics who last week signed a motion opposing the
European Communities Finance bill fell into line in the face of Mr John
Major's determination to call a general election if the bill was defeated.
But seven hard-core MPs abstained in a crucial vote on a Labour amendment.
They were: Sir Teddy Taylor (Southend E), Mrs Teresa Gorman (Billericay), Mr
Tony Marlow (Northampton N), Mr Nicholas Budgen (Wolverhampton SW), Mr
Richard Shepherd (Aldridge Brownhills), Mr John Wilkinson (Ruislip
Northwood) and Mr Christopher Gill (Ludlow).
Mr Michael Carttiss (Great Yarmouth) abstained on the second reading
division, after voting with the government on the amendment.
Mr Richard Ryder, the government chief whip, immediately wrote to the seven
MPs who abstained on the amendment, withdrawing the Conservative whip -
effectively suspending them from the parliamentary party. It was unclear
whether Mr Carttiss would also be suspended.
Withdrawal of the whip is a serious punishment which bans MPs from taking
part in the 1922 committee of Tory backbenchers, from sitting on back-bench
Tory committees, or voting on party issues such as the election of a new
leader.
Tory MPs said it was the first mass withdrawal of the whip since the second
world war. The consequences could be serious for the government, which
theoretically loses their support and sees its majority cut from 14 to zero.
In theory, Mr Major will find himself leading a government with a Commons
minority of two if Mr Carttiss is also disciplined, and three if Labour, as
expected, wins the forthcoming by-election in Dudley West. He could even
find himself with a minority of five if Sir Richard Body (Holland with
Boston), carries out a threat to resign the whip in protest at the drift of
government policy.
In practice, Mr Major can rely on the support of the rebels on most issues,
and on the 10 Ulster unionist MPs, all of whom voted with the government in
both divisions last night. However, the technical loss of support will make
the management of the government's parliamentary business more difficult,
and could threaten control of important parliamentary committees.
Most of the rebels will probably try to emulate Mr Rupert Allason (Torbay),
whose suspension from the Tory whip for abstaining in the Maastricht vote
last year, was lifted after he apologised and demonstrated an impeccable
voting record of support for the government.
If they remain in the cold, they could be prevented from standing as
official Conservative candidates at the next general election, effectively
ending their parliamentary careers.
Some rebels, including Mrs Gorman and Mr Wilkinson, say their constituency
organisations have already been warned that they must deselect their rebel
MPs or face disbandment and replacement by more compliant local officials.
The hardliners sat defiantly on the Commons benches through the divisions,
chatting amiably to less courageous Eurosceptics, and making no attempt to
hide their refusal to support the bill.
All are long-time opponents of the EU. Sir Teddy, for example, has
campaigned against British membership for longer than most MPs have been in
parliament. He told the Commons: 'I am not in any way trying to rock the
government. But, quite frankly, I hope the government should accept that
there are some of us who would think it outrageous, impossible and wrong to
vote for extra cash for the EU.'
Mrs Gorman, a right-wing populist who is frequently at odds with senior
ministers, was the only Tory MP to question the cost of the contributions
deal in the immediate aftermath of its negotiation by Mr Major at the 1992
Edinburgh summit.
Mr Budgen may have more problems than most of the rebels because he does not
have the full support of his constituency organisation.
Mr Gill, who has the strong backing of his constituency party, said he was
resigned to losing the whip. 'If the constituency wants to be represented by
a sheep then they can go down to Ludlow livestock market and buy one,' he
said.
Mr Wilkinson likened Mr Major's attitude to Brussels to the appeasement of
Adolf Hitler by Neville Chamberlain. 'The danger is that, like Neville
Chamberlain, Mr Major will be swept away from office - perhaps as a
consequence of his weakness - some two years hence,' he said.
Last night the lobbies of the Commons were echoing with the sound of less
courageous Euro-sceptics explaining away their unwillingness to join the
rebellion. The repentant rebels all had cogent reasons for backing down:
some feared deselection, others accepted the government's promises on EU
fraud, many were keeping their powder dry for the 1996 inter-governmental
conference.
</TEXT>
<XX>
