<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / MPs leave sickbeds to support PM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was the most vivid indication of the government's despair. For the first
time since the cliffhanger divisions over the Maastricht treaty, Tory MPs
hobbled into the Commons from their sickbeds to save Mr John Major's
administration, James Blitz writes.
Under parliamentary rules, MPs cannot vote by proxy. They must walk through
the division lobbies to have their votes counted. And amid continuing
uncertainty about how many Tories would rebel, government whips realised
they would have to bring out every last supporter to pass the European
finance bill.
Mr Julian Critchley, the MP for Aldershot, Hampshire, was wheeled into the
chamber in a wheelchair, grinning at the Tory benches.
Mr Geoffrey Dickens, the MP for Littleborough, braved serious illness to
turn up for the vote. He stunned MPs on all sides by making a typically
boisterous intervention shortly before the division, before engaging in a
lengthy conversation with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor.
Another MP who went to trouble to support the prime minister was Mr Patrick
Nicholls, who resigned as a Tory party vice-chairman last week after calling
the French 'a nation of collaborators'. Mr Nicholls, the MP for Teignbridge,
Devon, arrived wearing a neck brace after postponing an operation. Tory wags
privately claimed that the MP, who did a round of pro-government interviews,
was making amends for his gaffe.
However, there were some absentees. Most notable was Sir Nicholas Fairbairn,
the maverick MP for Perth and Kinross, who is thought to have stayed away
while recovering from a virus.
</TEXT>
