<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Tube to unveil Heathrow plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London Underground will today unveil plans for a Pounds 70m 1 1/4 -mile
extension of the Piccadilly Line to the proposed fifth terminal at Heathrow
Airport.
If London Underground's plans are approved work could start in 1997 and the
new extension and station would become operational in 2002, when Terminal 5
is due to open.
The Underground is applying to Mr Brian Mawhinney, transport secretary, for
permission to extend the line under the Transport and Works Act - avoiding
the need for a parliamentary bill.
Objectors have seven weeks to register their concerns with the Department of
Transport. These will then be considered by London Underground and Heathrow
Airport. A public inquiry into Terminal 5 is expected to start in May.
Work will involve an extension west of the existing station for Heathrow
terminals 1, 2 and 3. All trains will serve that station with some running
on to Terminal 4 and some to Terminal 5. About 30m air passengers are
expected to use Terminal 5 each year.
Work on the Pounds 300m Heathrow Express rail link between Heathrow and
Paddington Station was stopped after a tunnel collapse last month.
</TEXT>
