FT  29 NOV 94 / OECD deal over chief in doubt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A breakthrough in the deadlock over who should head the Organisation for
Economic Co-operation and Development, the industrial world's economic
think-tank, was in the balance yesterday after a meeting of OECD ambassadors
was adjourned for 24 hours. Hopes for a new secretary-general were raised
last week when Washington grudgingly agreed to a compromise deal. But
diplomats said a Franco-Canadian consensus eluded the 25 nations at their
two-hour meeting. They agreed to meet again today when they will have to
come up with a solution because the mandate of a stand-in head expires the
next day. Under the proposed compromise, Frenchman Jean-Claude Paye - whose
second five-year term ended in September - would be reappointed for 18
months and Canada's Donald Johnston would then take a full five-year tenure.
Several countries, particularly Japan, were said to be opposed to this.
