<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / EU lifts arms embargo against Syria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Union lifted its eight-year arms embargo on Syria last night
following a thawing of relations, a move criticised by Mr Shimon Peres,
Israel's foreign minister, as a mistake unless Damascus was willing to
negotiate peace with Israel.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, told reporters the decision
had been nodded through at the General Affairs Council.
The embargo was put in place in 1986 after allegations of Syrian involvement
in a thwarted attempt to smuggle explosives onto an Israeli El Al airliner
at London's Heathrow airport.
Other sanctions, such as bans on low-level diplomatic meetings were
gradually lifted between 1987 and 1990, when Syria sided with the west in
the Gulf War.
'Before the Syrians move, why lift. . . the embargo? Let them move and maybe
then there won't be a need for an arms embargo?' Mr Peres told reporters. 'I
don't know why the Syrians were so shy. If they want to have peace, why hide
away?'
At the same time, Mr Peres and Mr Yassir Arafat, chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organisation made some progress towards ironing out their
differences over the Palestinian peace process.
Both men, visiting Brussels on the eve of an international donor conference
intended to speed up aid flows to the Palestinian authority in Gaza and
Jericho, emphasised that recent acts of violence in the Middle East would
not be allowed to scupper progress made so far. 'We will make this peace
process a success,' said Mr Peres. 'We will not stop en route.'
There were few details on the talks. Neither side was particularly
forthcoming on the issues dividing them, including Israeli delays in
withdrawing from the West Bank and its action in sealing off Israel to
Palestinian workers resident in Gaza or the delays in holding elections in
the Palestinian territories.
Referring to the recent bloody clashes between Islamic fundamentalists and
both Palestinian police and his own Fatah faction, Mr Arafat said: 'I insist
on very rapid elections to see who has the support of the people; Hamas or
Fatah?'
'In my opinion the Israelis understand our need for a quick election, but at
the same time we have to understand their necessity for security which is
one of their main items,' said Mr Arafat.
He said that the most important thing for the Palestinians was that all
donors kept their promises, pointing out that the Palestinians had so far
only received a fraction of the total promised.
A senior British official said Mr Hurd had 'floated some ideas' on taking
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations forward. 'There is a real need on all sides
to make clear what the tangible benefits of the peace process are,' said the
UK official.
A successful outcome to the Palestine donors conference today and tomorrow
is regarded as a vital first step in this direction.
</TEXT>
