<PROFILE>_AN-EK2CXAA9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941129
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / World Trade News: US rallies for Uruguay Round vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Opponents and supporters of the Uruguay Round global trade pact yesterday
were lobbying feverishly for votes ahead of today's vote in the House of
Representatives on the deal reached last December.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, yesterday predicted that the
House today would pass the legislation implementing the Round by 'a large
vote' in favour, sending it on to the Senate 'with overwhelming support' for
a vote on Thursday.
A serious hurdle was cleared last week when Senator Robert Dole, the
Republican leader, accepted a deal addressing his concerns about the dispute
settlement mechanism in the proposed World Trade Organisation.
But Mr Ralph Nader, the consumer activist and a leader of anti-Gatt forces,
said neither side could claim enough votes in the Senate, where 60 are
needed for passage, and no one in the Administration disputed him.
Mr Nader had one victory yesterday. Senator Hank Brown, a Colorado
Republican, took him up on his offer of Dollars 10,000 to any member of
Congress who would read the implementing legislation and pass a 12-question
test on the contents.
The senator, who had been leaning in favour of the pact, passed the test,
rejected the Dollars 10,000 and then announced he had decided to vote
against the pact.
'He realised the US would be paying 25 per cent of the costs while taking in
about 30 per cent of the imports and it would get only one vote out of 124,'
his spokesman said.
The trade pact battle, conducted when there is little else in the national
news, is receiving attention on a par with the fight over the North American
Free Trade Agreement. Opponents maintained that polls showed the US public
were against the deal. Mr Ross Perot, the Texas billionaire, has vowed to
start a third party if the deal passes.
In an effort to counter the negative messages, supporters, led by the
Alliance for Gatt Now, poured funds into television, radio and print.
Individual companies - Boeing, Merrill Lynch, and EDS - entered the fray,
and trade groups such as the Grocery Manufacturers of America called for 'a
vote of confidence in America's ability to succeed in a fair world trading
system'.
President Clinton held a rally with supporters, hoping to convince wavering
senators. The president said: 'It is not a Republican agreement or a
Democratic one. It is an American agreement designed to benefit all the
American people in every region of our country and from every walk of life.'
The US Business and Industrial Council, a protectionist business group,
placed a large advertisement in the Washington Post listing names of 91
defeated and retiring senators and house members. 'The Gatt vote will be
very close,' it said. 'This means that the defeated lame duck Congressmen
and senators - many of whom will soon become lobbyists for special and
foreign interests - will get to decide OUR economic future.'
All weekend the CNN television network ran an advertisement with pigs -
designated as members - at a trough. 'Some call it a global trade deal, but
hidden inside is billions of special interest pork,' it says. 'Call your
senators today and tell them don't butcher the budget. Take the fat out of
Gatt.'
Three former presidents - George Bush, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter -
released a letter to the president calling the pact 'a bridge from the
post-war world of half a century ago to the post-Cold War world which is
being forged today'.
</TEXT>
