<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Decision on 'Swatchmobile' site
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The pioneering micro city car that is being developed by Mercedes-Benz, the
German executive and luxury carmaker and SMH, the Swiss watchmaker, is
likely to be produced at a new plant in France or Germany. The board of
Micro-Compact-Car, the joint venture formed earlier this year by
Mercedes-Benz and SMH, is due to meet on Friday and is expected to make a
preliminary decision on a production location. Final approval of the site is
likely to be given by the boards of the parent companies next week. The
Alsace region of France and the German state of Baden-Wurttemberg are
believed to be the front-runners to win the project. Mr Hans-Jurg Schar,
marketing and sales director of MCC, said that the so-called 'Swatchmobile'
would be built either in France or Germany and not in Switzerland. SMH and
its chief executive Mr Nicolas Hayek had hoped to bring production of the
micro car to Switzerland, but Mr Schar said that the 'offers from Biel and
Oensingen cannot compete with sites that receive European Union subsidies'.
Switzerland, which is not a member of the EU, has some of the highest labour
costs in the world. Mercedes-Benz, which holds a 51 per cent stake in the
venture, and SMH, the maker of Swatch watches, which holds 49 per cent, are
aiming to launch the 'micro compact car' in Europe by 1997/98 with an
initial production capacity of 100,000 to 150,000 cars a year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Micro-Compact-Car.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
