<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 94 / Carsberg to quit early as fair trading head
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Bryan Carsberg, Britain's senior competition regulator, is to step down
as director-general of fair trading next May, three years into his five-year
term.
Sir Bryan, a former accountancy professor, is quitting the Office of Fair
Trading to become secretary-general of the IASC - the international
financial reporting organisation.
Although his decision will cause some embarrassment to the government it has
not come as a surprise. Sir Bryan is known to be frustrated by his role at
the OFT as the government has watered down competition policy in favour of
promoting industry.
As director-general of telecommunications from 1984 to 1992, Sir Bryan was
the UK's first privatised utilities regulator, and when he moved to the OFT
it was widely expected he would expand the role. Observers thought he would
eventually take full responsibility for regulation and oversee other utility
watchdogs.
However, his appointment to the OFT coincided with that of Mr Michael
Heseltine as trade and industry secretary and with the change of government
policy on competition.
Sir Bryan, who is on a two-day business trip to Paris, was unavailable for
comment last night, but an OFT official denied that there was any rift
between him and Mr Heseltine. 'It is a question of him wanting to go to
something rather an escape from something,' he said.
Ironically, the announcement of his departure comes when the OFT is much
busier than it has been for several months, vetting both the British
Aerospace and GEC bids for VSEL, the submarine builder, and the proposed
merger between the Leeds and Halifax building societies.
Sir Bryan moves to the IASC for an initial five-year term, but his contract
is renewable. The appointment delighted the accounting body, which draws up
model financial reporting standards. Sir Bryan said in a statement issued
yesterday by the IASC: 'The move towards more competitive global capital
markets and the continuing progress of multinational companies create a
strong need for common accounting rules which can be applied in all
countries and which will be accepted by all stock exchanges.'
Mr Eiichi Shiratori, chairman of the IASC, said: 'I am very pleased that the
IASC has been able to attract such a well qualified person as its
secretary-general at such an important time in its development.'
The IASC is playing an increasing role in regulating accounting standards at
a time when the growth in international trading is giving it influence in
bringing together national regulators.
Carsberg quits Heseltine's long shadow, Page 11
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
